INSERT INTO `claim_evidence` VALUES (1,1,'supports','strong','The scale of this study — 100K+ engineers, 600+ companies, three years of longitudinal data from private repos — gives the 15–20% net productivity finding substantially more weight than smaller or vendor-sponsored studies.',NULL),(1,2,'qualifies','strong','The matrix reveals that the 15–20% average hides a wide distribution — some task contexts see 30–40% gains while others see near-zero, making the average potentially misleading for any specific team.',NULL),(2,3,'supports','moderate','This single-team case study directly demonstrates the rework phenomenon: total code output rose after AI adoption but rework volume also increased, showing how gross gains overstate net productivity improvement.',NULL),(3,4,'supports','strong','Provides empirical evidence for one of the five moderating factors (language popularity), demonstrating measurable variation from positive to negative productivity impact along this dimension.',NULL),(4,2,'supports','strong','Directly quantifies the claim with a structured matrix across 136 teams and 27 companies, showing the full range from 30–40% gains (low-complexity greenfield) to 0–10% (high-complexity brownfield).',NULL),(5,4,'supports','strong','Directly measures the claim across the language popularity spectrum, showing not just reduced gains but actual negative productivity impact for complex tasks in COBOL, Haskell, and Elixir.',NULL),(6,5,'supports','moderate','Context window degradation is one of three mechanisms proposed for why larger codebases see smaller AI gains. This paper provides direct evidence for the context-length component.',NULL),(6,7,'qualifies','moderate','Provides a theoretical framework for the codebase-size relationship (context windows, signal-to-noise, dependencies), but the presenter himself characterizes this as illustrative rather than rigorously measured — meaning the claim\'s strength depends on future empirical validation.',NULL),(7,1,'supports','moderate','The study\'s scale and design (private repos, longitudinal, cross-sectional) implicitly demonstrates the methodological gaps in smaller studies that rely on public repos, greenfield tasks, or surveys.',NULL),(7,6,'supports','moderate','Provides empirical evidence that the survey-based methodology used by many AI productivity studies produces unreliable results, supporting the claim that such studies are methodologically flawed.',NULL),(7,9,'supports','moderate','Fowler identifies a specific methodological flaw â€” failure to distinguish workflow types â€” that reinforces the broader claim about flawed productivity studies.',NULL),(8,6,'supports','moderate','Directly measures the claim — 30-percentile-point average error, only 1 in 3 within correct quartile. Moderate strength due to small sample size (n=43) limiting generalizability.',NULL),(9,5,'supports','moderate','Provides specific quantitative benchmarks (90% at 1K tokens to 50% at 32K tokens) across multiple models. Moderate strength because this is external research that may not directly map to current enterprise AI tools.',NULL),(11,9,'supports','moderate','Fowler direct observation of workflow differences supports the claim that surveys conflating workflows are flawed, though this is expert opinion without controlled data.',NULL),(12,9,'supports','moderate','Fowler reports that his most productive peers prefer agentic approaches over autocomplete, directly supporting this observation-level claim.',NULL),(14,10,'supports','moderate','Historical precedent from canals, railroads, and the internet provides a theoretical basis for the bubble claim, though historical analogy is suggestive rather than deterministic.',NULL),(15,11,'supports','moderate','Parsons is a recognized technologist (former CTO of Thoughtworks) and the framing is logically coherent, though it is a philosophical reframing rather than empirical finding.',NULL),(16,12,'supports','weak','Practical recommendation from an experienced practitioner, but no empirical evidence on whether this approach actually yields better outcomes.',NULL),(17,15,'supports','weak','Theoretical argument drawing an analogy to other engineering disciplines. Conceptually interesting but not empirically grounded.',NULL),(18,13,'supports','strong','Willison is a recognized authority on LLM security, the framework is specific and actionable, and the attack vector described is technically demonstrated.',NULL),(18,16,'supports','strong','Schneier\'s expert opinion that no agentic AI system is currently secure against prompt injection corroborates the claim that LLMs dramatically expand attack surface with these architectural properties.',NULL),(18,17,'supports','strong','The Lethal Trifecta definition by Willison directly supports and refines claim 18 by naming the specific architectural combination that makes attack surfaces catastrophically dangerous, not merely larger.',NULL),(18,18,'supports','strong','The AgentFlayer attack is a concrete case study validating the claim that the combination of private data access, untrusted content, and external communication makes certain agent architectures fundamentally unsafe.',NULL),(19,14,'supports','weak','Anecdotal observation from a single practitioner. Widely reported by others but not systematically measured here.',NULL),(20,12,'supports','weak','The recommendation to never use LLMs for deterministic calculation follows logically from the hallucination framing but is based on expert judgment, not measured data.',NULL),(21,16,'supports','strong','Schneier\'s direct assertion that zero agentic systems are secure against prompt injection, and that the root cause is the adversarial environment inherent to LLM inputs, directly supports the claim that this is systemic and unsolved.',NULL),(21,17,'supports','moderate','Willison\'s Lethal Trifecta framework implicitly rests on the premise that prompt injection cannot be eliminated â€” the trifecta only matters if injection is possible. His inability to recommend a safe browser extension architecture corroborates the claim.',NULL),(21,18,'supports','strong','The AgentFlayer attack is a concrete, working exploit that demonstrates prompt injection in a realistic agentic workflow, corroborating that the vulnerability exists and is exploitable in practice, not just in theory.',NULL),(22,17,'supports','strong','This evidence IS the Lethal Trifecta definition by its originator Simon Willison â€” it is the primary source for the framework claim.',NULL),(22,18,'supports','strong','The AgentFlayer attack is a worked example that validates the trifecta framework: all three legs (sensitive JWT tokens, attacker-controlled Zendesk ticket, public Jira write access) were simultaneously present and exploited.',NULL),(22,28,'supports','moderate','Willison\'s two scope-defining assertions â€” any internet access exfiltrates data, any non-user content is potentially untrusted â€” clarify the breadth of two of the three trifecta legs, reinforcing the framework\'s practical scope.',NULL),(23,16,'supports','strong','Schneier\'s verbatim statement provides direct authoritative support: \"we have zero agentic AI systems that are secure against these attacks.\" As a recognized security authority, this constitutes strong expert opinion evidence.',NULL),(23,18,'supports','moderate','The AgentFlayer case study demonstrates that at least one realistic attack chain was executable in the published timeframe, corroborating the claim that no system was secure against all such attacks.',NULL),(23,20,'supports','moderate','The steganographic browser attack on two separate LLM-powered browsers shows the vulnerability manifested across multiple independent products, supporting the breadth of the \"no agentic system is secure\" claim.',NULL),(24,20,'supports','strong','The steganographic attack on two LLM-powered browsers is a concrete case study showing the vector is real and already exploited, moving the claim beyond theoretical concern to demonstrated vulnerability.',NULL),(24,21,'supports','strong','Willison\'s direct quote â€” \"I strongly expect that the entire concept of an agentic browser extension is fatally flawed and cannot be built safely\" â€” is the primary evidence. As the originator of the Lethal Trifecta analysis and a leading practitioner, his expectation carries significant weight.',NULL),(24,22,'qualifies','moderate','The Playwright MCP counter-example shows that browser-based LLM tooling CAN be made safer by isolating credentials â€” qualifying the claim that all browser-based architectures are unsafe and pointing to the specific design flaw (authenticated session access) that makes extensions problematic.',NULL),(25,17,'supports','strong','The Lethal Trifecta definition is the logical foundation for the mitigation strategy â€” if the trifecta requires all three conditions, removing any one breaks the attack chain. This evidence establishes the causal model the mitigation principle depends on.',NULL),(25,22,'supports','strong','Microsoft\'s Playwright MCP is a working implementation of this principle: by removing the sensitive data leg (no cookies, no credentials), the product achieves a materially safer posture compared to authenticated browser extensions.',NULL),(25,28,'supports','moderate','Willison\'s scope assertions (any internet access exfiltrates, any non-user content is untrusted) help define which leg is most reducible in a given workflow â€” knowing the scope of each leg is necessary to act on the mitigation principle.',NULL),(26,16,'supports','moderate','Schneier\'s characterization of the problem as existential and largely unaddressed by vendors motivates why a session-level architectural mitigation is necessary â€” vendors are not solving this at the platform level.',NULL),(26,23,'supports','moderate','The Principle of Least Privilege is the theoretical foundation for the task decomposition pattern â€” the evidence establishes the security principle that the recommendation operationalizes.',NULL),(26,24,'supports','strong','This evidence IS the five-step decomposition pattern. It directly supports the claim by providing the specific implementation and its rationale (least privilege at session level, contains compromise to one stage).',NULL),(27,23,'supports','moderate','The Principle of Least Privilege applied at the container level is still subject to the same logic: if the container itself violates least privilege by having both credentials and untrusted content, isolation buys nothing. The theoretical principle explains the caveat.',NULL),(27,24,'supports','moderate','The five-step task decomposition note explicitly states that container isolation does not prevent the Lethal Trifecta from being triggered inside the container if credentials and untrusted content are present simultaneously â€” directly corroborating the \"reduces but does not eliminate\" claim.',NULL),(27,25,'supports','moderate','The Claude Code Dev Container reference implementation is a concrete sandboxing example that also illustrates the caveat: it defaults to --dangerously-skip-permissions, showing that even a purpose-built sandbox can be misconfigured in ways that undermine its protection.',NULL),(28,17,'supports','moderate','Willison\'s Lethal Trifecta framework explains WHY vetting matters more â€” each MCP server integrated into an agentic workflow is a potential injection conduit or exfiltration channel. More integrations multiply the attack surface.',NULL),(28,26,'supports','moderate','The MCP Registry\'s status as a directory rather than a certification illustrates the gap: even an official registry does not provide security vetting, meaning practitioners cannot rely on registries as a vetting shortcut and must apply their own discipline.',NULL),(29,16,'supports','moderate','Schneier\'s characterization of the security problem as existential and largely ignored by vendors reinforces why developer responsibility matters: if platform vendors are not solving the problem, individual developers bear the accountability for how they deploy agents.',NULL),(29,27,'supports','strong','Kim and Yegge\'s head-chef metaphor is the primary evidence for this claim â€” it directly asserts the responsibility principle and provides a memorable framing. The context (Vibe Coding, 2025) gives it practitioner credibility.',NULL),(30,18,'supports','moderate','AgentFlayer uses public Jira write access (a legitimate task-related capability) as the exfiltration channel, corroborating that even purpose-appropriate internet access can be weaponized.',NULL),(30,19,'supports','strong','The image-load exfiltration technique is a concrete, specific exploit that demonstrates the claim: a GET request to a PNG URL with a query parameter is indistinguishable from a legitimate image load but transmits data to an attacker. This validates the claim with a worked example.',NULL),(30,28,'supports','strong','Willison\'s direct assertion â€” \"any internet access can exfiltrate data\" â€” is the expert opinion form of the claim. Combined with the image-load case study, strong and moderate evidence converge on the same conclusion.',NULL),(31,18,'supports','strong','AgentFlayer specifically targets JWT tokens identifiable by a string prefix in files or context. The attack would be ineffective if credentials were never in files accessible to the LLM, directly validating the recommendation.',NULL),(31,19,'supports','moderate','The image-load exfiltration technique illustrates how an LLM with file-read access and network access can silently read credential files and transmit them â€” exactly the attack vector the recommendation is designed to prevent.',NULL),(31,23,'supports','moderate','The Principle of Least Privilege provides the theoretical foundation: storing credentials in-memory-only implements least privilege for the sensitive data leg â€” they are available only when explicitly needed, not persistently accessible.',NULL),(32,17,'supports','moderate','The Lethal Trifecta framework identifies external communication capability as the enabling leg â€” MCP servers with write/publish access are precisely the mechanism that activates this leg in typical developer workflows.',NULL),(32,18,'supports','strong','AgentFlayer uses a Jira MCP server\'s public comment write capability as the exfiltration channel â€” this is a direct, worked demonstration of the claim. The attack would be impossible without an MCP server that can publish to a public channel.',NULL),(32,28,'supports','moderate','Willison\'s assertion that any internet access can exfiltrate data establishes the general principle; MCP write/publish capabilities are a specific and particularly capable instance of internet access that amplifies this risk.',NULL),(33,17,'supports','moderate','Willison\'s Lethal Trifecta analysis establishes why registry status matters â€” each MCP server is a potential injection conduit. The gap between \"listed in registry\" and \"security-audited\" is consequential given this threat model.',NULL),(33,26,'supports','strong','This evidence directly documents the MCP Registry\'s current state at the time of publication: it functions as a directory, not a security certification. The evidence IS the claim\'s supporting documentation.',NULL),(34,16,'qualifies','weak','Evidence about constraints enabling output quality from a different source; corroborates the pattern but from a different domain context.',NULL),(34,29,'supports','moderate','Production deployment across multiple client engagements is the primary validation that structured conventions are necessary for reliable agentic value â€” though without quantitative measurement.',NULL),(34,31,'supports','moderate','The two-layer architecture (deterministic orchestration + bounded execution) being the consistent pattern across all successful implementations directly supports the claim that structure is required.',NULL),(34,44,'supports','moderate','The source\'s direct counter to the autonomy narrative â€” asserting constraints enable reliability â€” confirms the claim from a practitioner perspective.',NULL),(35,14,'supports','weak','Artifact frontmatter tracking (draft/in-review/approved/complete) and folder conventions demonstrate the operational mechanics of SDD in practice.',NULL),(35,29,'supports','moderate','The source\'s production validation across multiple engagements supports SDD as a proven rather than theoretical approach.',NULL),(35,33,'supports','moderate','The convergent design decision between Spec Kit and Kiro â€” both separating persistent project context from per-feature specs, both stored in the repo â€” provides cross-product validation of the SDD pattern, though the comparison lacks citation.',NULL),(36,29,'supports','weak','Practitioner observation from multiple client engagements that handoff breakdown is the consistent failure point gives this claim credibility, though it remains anecdotal.',NULL),(37,31,'supports','moderate','The two-layer architecture\'s consistency across all successful implementations implies the absence of self-orchestration is a necessary design condition.',NULL),(37,32,'supports','moderate','Observed failure modes (skipped steps, circular dependencies, analysis loops) on larger codebases are specific, concrete behaviors â€” not hypothetical â€” providing direct evidence against self-orchestration.',NULL),(38,32,'supports','moderate','The contrast is explicit: observed failure modes in self-orchestrating agents versus the reliable enforcement of rule-based engines is the direct basis for this claim.',NULL),(38,36,'supports','moderate','The specific workflow engine rules (requirements before task generation, architecture before implementation, dependency satisfaction before execution) demonstrate concrete enforcement mechanisms.',NULL),(38,39,'qualifies','moderate','The claim that this observation lacks quantitative backing means the superiority of rule-based engines is practitioner-reported, not measured.',NULL),(39,29,'supports','moderate','Production validation across multiple engagements provides practitioner-level support for specialization being the reliable design choice.',NULL),(39,39,'qualifies','moderate','The source acknowledges no quantitative benchmarks exist for this claim, meaning it rests on observed patterns rather than measured comparisons.',NULL),(39,43,'supports','moderate','The explicit microservices analogy frames specialization as the architecturally sound choice â€” a known pattern applied to agent design.',NULL),(40,29,'supports','moderate','Production use across multiple client engagements grounds the analogy in practice, not just theory.',NULL),(40,43,'supports','strong','The source makes this comparison explicitly, with the same tradeoff framing â€” one complex system vs. multiple simpler systems plus interface orchestration cost. Direct evidence for the analogy claim.',NULL),(41,9,'supports','moderate','The two-layer evaluation process (deterministic + critic agent) is a concrete implementation of the principle, described with sufficient detail to validate its application.',NULL),(41,37,'supports','moderate','The specific workflow engine rules enforcing completeness before phase progression directly instantiate the principle of inline evaluation preventing downstream error propagation.',NULL),(42,29,'supports','moderate','Production deployment validates the two-layer approach as a working pattern, not just a design proposal.',NULL),(42,37,'supports','strong','The two-layer evaluation is described with specific implementation detail â€” linters, test suites, frontmatter presence, cross-reference resolution in layer one; agentic judgment checks in layer two â€” providing strong case-study support.',NULL),(43,34,'supports','moderate','The concrete example (async queue assumption surfacing in PR diff) demonstrates the mechanism: assumptions become structured diff items, reviewable and correctable, persisting in version history.',NULL),(43,35,'supports','moderate','The reviewer-correction loop â€” assumption rejected, agent reworks, correction becomes documented decision retrievable by future agents â€” demonstrates how institutional memory accumulates over time.',NULL),(44,34,'supports','strong','The specific example (sync vs. async queue decision logged as structured assumption in PR diff) directly illustrates the recommendation in concrete operational terms.',NULL),(44,35,'supports','moderate','The correction loop â€” reviewer rejects assumption, agent reworks, correction persists as decision â€” demonstrates the downstream value of structured logging over freeform notes.',NULL),(45,31,'supports','moderate','The deterministic orchestration + bounded execution architecture being the consistent success pattern is the empirical basis for the claim that structure is the enabling factor.',NULL),(45,32,'supports','moderate','Observed failure modes when agents were given meta-level autonomy provide the direct contrast case â€” more autonomy produced worse results.',NULL),(45,44,'supports','strong','The source explicitly positions this as a counter-narrative to autonomy-as-improvement, directly articulating the constraint-over-capability argument.',NULL),(46,38,'supports','strong','The source provides specific examples (specs/REQ-001-*/, REQ-* prefixes, context/ folder) demonstrating how conventions simultaneously organize for humans and enable machine parsing â€” direct evidence for the dual-purpose claim.',NULL),(46,42,'supports','moderate','Artifact frontmatter (draft/in-review/approved/complete) is another instance of the same pattern: human-readable status that the workflow engine also uses programmatically.',NULL),(47,39,'supports','strong','The source explicitly self-reports this limitation in its Gaps and Caveats section, making the caveat direct and high-confidence evidence for the claim about absence of quantitative backing.',NULL),(47,40,'supports','moderate','The acknowledged promotional context (QuantumBlack author prominently featuring QuantumBlack tooling) compounds the lack of quantitative data as a credibility qualifier.',NULL),(47,41,'supports','moderate','The scope limitation (greenfield only) narrows the generalizability of even the practitioner observations that do exist.',NULL);
