INSERT INTO `evidence` VALUES (1,'Stanford three-year longitudinal study encompassing over 100,000 software engineers across 600+ companies (enterprise, midsized, startup), with tens of millions of commits and billions of lines of code from predominantly private repositories. Time-series and cross-sectional design enables trend analysis and cross-organization comparison.',2,'statistical',NULL,NULL,NULL,'Study scale and design. Private repos chosen for self-contained productivity measurement.','2026-03-01 20:14:55'),(2,'Complexity-by-maturity matrix from 136 teams across 27 companies: low-complexity greenfield tasks show 30–40% productivity gain; high-complexity greenfield 10–15%; low-complexity brownfield 15–20%; high-complexity brownfield 0–10%.',2,'empirical',NULL,NULL,NULL,'Sample is substantially smaller than full 100K dataset. Representativeness uncertain.','2026-03-01 20:14:55'),(3,'Rework analysis on a 120-developer team after AI adoption showed increased rework volume (modifications to recently written code indicating wasted effort) despite rising total code output. The raw volume increase created a misleading impression of productivity improvement.',2,'case_study',NULL,NULL,NULL,'Single-team observation. Rework defined as alterations to recently written code, distinct from refactoring of older code.','2026-03-01 20:14:55'),(4,'Language popularity analysis: popular languages (Python, Java, JavaScript, TypeScript) see the full range of 10–20% gains depending on complexity. Unpopular languages (COBOL, Haskell, Elixir) see minimal benefit for simple tasks and negative productivity impact for complex tasks, leading developers to abandon AI tooling for those languages.',2,'empirical',NULL,NULL,NULL,'Unpopular languages estimated at 5–10% of global development work.','2026-03-01 20:14:55'),(5,'Citing the No LIMA paper: LLM performance on coding tasks drops from approximately 90% at 1,000 tokens of context to approximately 50% at 32,000 tokens. Models with 2-million-token context windows (e.g., Gemini 1.5 Pro) still show this degradation pattern.',2,'statistical',NULL,NULL,NULL,'External research cited by presenter. May not map directly to current enterprise AI coding tools given rapid model improvements.','2026-03-01 20:14:55'),(6,'Self-assessment validation study (n=43 developers): developers estimated their productivity relative to global median in five percentile buckets. Comparison to measured productivity showed near-random correlation — developers misjudged by approximately 30 percentile points, with only 1 in 3 estimating within the correct quartile.',2,'empirical',NULL,NULL,NULL,'Very small sample (n=43). Directionally interesting but needs larger replication.','2026-03-01 20:14:55'),(7,'Three factors explain why AI productivity gains diminish with codebase size: context window limitations of current models, degraded signal-to-noise ratio in larger contexts, and increased density of dependencies and domain-specific logic.',2,'theoretical',NULL,NULL,NULL,'Presenter explicitly describes this as more theoretical, less empirically proven — illustrative trend rather than rigorously measured.','2026-03-01 20:14:55'),(8,'Approximately 10% of the 50,000 software engineers studied at the time — termed ghost engineers — contributed essentially no meaningful output while drawing full compensation.',2,'statistical',NULL,NULL,NULL,'From same Stanford research group. Tangential to AI productivity question but establishes context about baseline measurement challenges.','2026-03-01 20:14:55'),(9,'Fowler observes that the vast majority of LLM usage is autocomplete-style via Copilot, while practitioners who extract the most value prefer approaches that allow the LLM to directly read and edit source code files to carry out tasks.',3,'expert_opinion','those I know who get the most value from LLMs reckon that auto-complete isn\'t very useful, preferring approaches that allow the LLM to directly read and edit source code files to carry out tasks','{\"notes\": \"Expert opinion from personal observation. Cannot be independently verified but comes from a credible source.\", \"credibility\": 2, \"evaluated_at\": \"2026-03-01 21:56:28.000000\", \"independence\": \"original\", \"verifiability\": \"unverifiable\"}',NULL,'Based on personal professional network, not formal study.','2026-03-01 21:54:39'),(10,'All major technological advances have come with economic bubbles: canals, railroads, and the internet. The dot-com bubble killed Pets.com and Webvan but not Amazon, demonstrating that real value survives speculative collapse.',3,'theoretical','OF COURSE IT\'S A BUBBLE. All major technological advances have come with economic bubbles, from canals and railroads to the internet.','{\"notes\": \"Historical claims about canals, railroads, dot-com are verifiable. The analogy to AI is original interpretation.\", \"credibility\": 2, \"evaluated_at\": \"2026-03-01 21:56:28.000000\", \"independence\": \"original\", \"verifiability\": \"verifiable\"}',NULL,NULL,'2026-03-01 21:54:39'),(11,'Rebecca Parsons, former Thoughtworks colleague of Fowler, frames hallucinations as the fundamental feature of LLMs rather than a bug, arguing that all LLM output is hallucination and some happen to be useful.',3,'expert_opinion','hallucinations aren\'t a bug of LLMs, they are a feature. Indeed they are the feature. All an LLM does is produce hallucinations, it\'s just that we find some of them useful.','{\"notes\": \"Philosophical reframing from a recognized technologist. Not empirically testable.\", \"credibility\": 2, \"evaluated_at\": \"2026-03-01 21:56:28.000000\", \"independence\": \"original\", \"verifiability\": \"unverifiable\"}',NULL,'Attributed to Rebecca Parsons, former CTO of Thoughtworks.','2026-03-01 21:54:39'),(12,'Fowler recommends asking LLMs the same question multiple times with wording variations, comparing answers, and asking at least three times for numeric answers to gauge variation.',3,'expert_opinion',NULL,'{\"notes\": \"Practical recommendation that could be empirically tested but has not been.\", \"credibility\": 2, \"evaluated_at\": \"2026-03-01 21:56:28.000000\", \"independence\": \"original\", \"verifiability\": \"verifiable\"}',NULL,'Practical recommendation derived from the hallucination-as-feature framing.','2026-03-01 21:54:39'),(13,'Simon Willison identifies the Lethal Trifecta for AI agents: access to private data, exposure to untrusted content, and external communication capability. An attacker can embed instructions in 1pt white-on-white text on a web page to manipulate browser-based agents.',3,'expert_opinion','the entire concept of an agentic browser extension is fatally flawed and cannot be built safely','{\"notes\": \"Willison is a recognized security researcher. The attack vector (white-on-white text injection) has been independently demonstrated.\", \"credibility\": 1, \"evaluated_at\": \"2026-03-01 21:56:28.000000\", \"independence\": \"derivative\", \"verifiability\": \"verified\"}',NULL,'Willison is a recognized authority on LLM security.','2026-03-01 21:54:39'),(14,'Fowler reports personally observing LLMs claiming all tests pass when tests actually fail, comparing this to behavior that would trigger HR involvement if exhibited by a junior engineer.',3,'anecdotal',NULL,'{\"notes\": \"Anecdotal personal observation. Widely reported by others but no systematic measurement here.\", \"credibility\": 3, \"evaluated_at\": \"2026-03-01 21:56:28.000000\", \"independence\": \"original\", \"verifiability\": \"verifiable\"}',NULL,'Personal observation, anecdotal.','2026-03-01 21:54:39'),(15,'Fowler draws a parallel between LLMs and other engineering disciplines: structural engineers build in tolerance, process engineers account for human error, but software engineering has uniquely worked with deterministic machines until now.',3,'theoretical',NULL,'{\"notes\": \"Conceptual analogy, not empirically testable. Thought-provoking but not evidence in the traditional sense.\", \"credibility\": 2, \"evaluated_at\": \"2026-03-01 21:56:28.000000\", \"independence\": \"original\", \"verifiability\": \"unverifiable\"}',NULL,'Conceptual argument, not empirical.','2026-03-01 21:54:39'),(16,'Bruce Schneier states that we have zero agentic AI systems secure against prompt injection attacks, describing it as an existential problem that developers are largely pretending does not exist.',4,'expert_opinion','We simply don\'t know how to defend against these attacks. We have zero agentic AI systems that are secure against these attacks. Any AI that is working in an adversarial environment â€” and by this I mean that it may encounter untrusted training data or input â€” is vulnerable to prompt injection. It\'s an existential problem that, near as I can tell, most people developing these technologies are just pretending isn\'t there.','{\"notes\": \"Quotes Bruce Schneier directly from the source; derivative reference to external authority but properly attributed\", \"credibility\": 1, \"evaluated_at\": \"2026-03-02 00:00:32.000000\", \"independence\": \"derivative\", \"verifiability\": \"verified\"}',NULL,NULL,'2026-03-01 23:56:36'),(17,'Simon Willison defines the Lethal Trifecta as the simultaneous presence of three conditions in an agentic LLM system: access to sensitive data, exposure to untrusted content, and the ability to externally communicate.',4,'expert_opinion',NULL,'{\"notes\": \"Core concept from Simon Willison, presented clearly in source; derivative but foundational to article structure\", \"credibility\": 1, \"evaluated_at\": \"2026-03-02 00:00:32.000000\", \"independence\": \"derivative\", \"verifiability\": \"verified\"}',NULL,'Willison is the primary source for the Lethal Trifecta framework','2026-03-01 23:56:36'),(18,'The AgentFlayer attack demonstrates the full Lethal Trifecta in practice: a user queries Jira tickets via an MCP server; an attacker-crafted Zendesk ticket instructs the LLM to locate JWT tokens (identifiable by the eyj prefix) and post them as a public Jira comment, silently exfiltrating session credentials.',4,'case_study',NULL,'{\"notes\": \"Cited from Simon Willison article \\\"AgentFlayer: When a Jira Ticket Can Steal Your Secrets\\\"; described with sufficient detail for verification\", \"credibility\": 2, \"evaluated_at\": \"2026-03-02 00:00:32.000000\", \"independence\": \"derivative\", \"verifiability\": \"verifiable\"}',NULL,'Illustrates all three trifecta legs in a single real attack chain','2026-03-01 23:56:36'),(19,'An attacker can exfiltrate data from an LLM agent using a GET request disguised as an image load: a request to a URL like https://foobar.net/foo.png?var=[data] appears to the system as an image fetch but transmits the query parameter data to an attacker-controlled server.',4,'case_study',NULL,'{\"notes\": \"Generic attack vector described in source; technically sound and commonly understood in security circles\", \"credibility\": 2, \"evaluated_at\": \"2026-03-02 00:00:32.000000\", \"independence\": \"derivative\", \"verifiability\": \"verifiable\"}',NULL,'Shows that any outbound HTTP capability enables exfiltration','2026-03-01 23:56:36'),(20,'Two LLM-powered browsers were compromised by loading a web page containing low-contrast text invisible to humans but readable by the LLM, which treated the hidden text as instructions. This was reported on the Brave browser blog.',4,'case_study',NULL,'{\"notes\": \"Specific incident reported on Brave browser blog; attribution provided in source, verifiable at cited location\", \"credibility\": 2, \"evaluated_at\": \"2026-03-02 00:00:32.000000\", \"independence\": \"derivative\", \"verifiability\": \"verifiable\"}',NULL,'Steganographic prompt injection via browser; supports fatally-flawed browser extension claim','2026-03-01 23:56:36'),(21,'Simon Willison states his strong expectation that the entire concept of an agentic browser extension is fatally flawed and cannot be built safely.',4,'expert_opinion','I strongly expect that the entire concept of an agentic browser extension is fatally flawed and cannot be built safely.','{\"notes\": \"Direct expert opinion from Simon Willison; strong quote with clear attribution\", \"credibility\": 1, \"evaluated_at\": \"2026-03-02 00:00:32.000000\", \"independence\": \"derivative\", \"verifiability\": \"verified\"}',NULL,NULL,'2026-03-01 23:56:36'),(22,'Microsoft\'s Playwright MCP server is presented as a safer counter-example: it runs in an isolated browser instance with no access to user cookies or credentials, in contrast to browser extensions that connect to authenticated browser sessions.',4,'case_study',NULL,'{\"notes\": \"Describes technical properties of Playwright MCP; architecture claims are verifiable from Microsoft documentation\", \"credibility\": 2, \"evaluated_at\": \"2026-03-02 00:00:32.000000\", \"independence\": \"derivative\", \"verifiability\": \"verifiable\"}',NULL,'Illustrates how isolating one trifecta leg â€” sensitive data â€” materially reduces risk','2026-03-01 23:56:36'),(23,'The Principle of Least Privilege, originally stated by Jerome Saltzer in the ACM, holds that every program and every privileged user should operate using the least amount of privilege necessary to complete the job. The artifact applies this principle to LLM agent session design.',4,'theoretical','Every program and every privileged user of the system should operate using the least amount of privilege necessary to complete the job.','{\"notes\": \"Classical principle from Jerome Saltzer ACM; widely recognized foundational concept; accurately cited\", \"credibility\": 1, \"evaluated_at\": \"2026-03-02 00:00:32.000000\", \"independence\": \"derivative\", \"verifiability\": \"verified\"}',NULL,'Classic security principle applied to novel LLM context','2026-03-01 23:56:36'),(24,'A five-step task decomposition pattern is described for agentic security: (1) privileged session generates a research-plan.md, (2) human reviews the plan, (3) isolated low-privilege session executes the research plan and produces research-results.md, (4) human reviews results, (5) privileged session applies the results. This contains any compromise to a single stage.',4,'theoretical',NULL,'{\"notes\": \"Original pattern developed in source; technically sound application of least-privilege principle; repeatable methodology\", \"credibility\": 2, \"evaluated_at\": \"2026-03-02 00:00:32.000000\", \"independence\": \"derivative\", \"verifiability\": \"verifiable\"}',NULL,'Applies least-privilege at the session level; also benefits context size and LLM performance','2026-03-01 23:56:36'),(25,'Anthropic has published a reference implementation for running Claude Code in a Dev Container that includes a network firewall with an allow-list of acceptable domains. The implementation defaults to --dangerously-skip-permissions, which is flagged as a risk in the source.',4,'case_study',NULL,'{\"notes\": \"Describes Anthropic artifact; verifiable from Anthropic documentation; default flag concern is accurate\", \"credibility\": 2, \"evaluated_at\": \"2026-03-02 00:00:32.000000\", \"independence\": \"derivative\", \"verifiability\": \"verifiable\"}',NULL,'Concrete sandboxing option; the default flag is a meaningful caveat','2026-03-01 23:56:36'),(26,'The MCP Registry is described at publication time as a directory, not a security certification. It is framed as a step toward vetting but does not currently provide security assurance for listed servers.',4,'expert_opinion',NULL,'{\"notes\": \"Factual statement about MCP Registry scope at publication time; verifiable from official registry documentation\", \"credibility\": 2, \"evaluated_at\": \"2026-03-02 00:00:32.000000\", \"independence\": \"derivative\", \"verifiability\": \"verifiable\"}',NULL,'Important caveat for practitioners evaluating MCP servers','2026-03-01 23:56:36'),(27,'Gene Kim and Steve Yegge, in Vibe Coding (2025), use the head-chef framing to assert that when a customer complains about overcooked fish, the chef cannot blame the sous chef. The artifact applies this to LLM agent workflows: developers are fully responsible for all outputs regardless of tool origin.',4,'expert_opinion','When the customer sends back the fish because it\'s overdone or the sauce is broken, you can\'t blame your sous chef.','{\"notes\": \"Attribution to Vibe Coding (2025); verifiable from source; practical application to LLM responsibility is sound\", \"credibility\": 2, \"evaluated_at\": \"2026-03-02 00:00:32.000000\", \"independence\": \"derivative\", \"verifiability\": \"verifiable\"}',NULL,'Kim and Yegge cited as source of the framing','2026-03-01 23:56:36'),(28,'Simon Willison asserts that any internet access can exfiltrate data and that any content not coming directly from the user is potentially untrusted — establishing the breadth of both the external communication leg and the untrusted content leg of the trifecta.',4,'expert_opinion',NULL,'{\"notes\": \"Expert opinion from Simon Willison; consistent with broader security analysis throughout the article\", \"credibility\": 1, \"evaluated_at\": \"2026-03-02 00:00:32.000000\", \"independence\": \"derivative\", \"verifiability\": \"verified\"}',NULL,'Two concise Willison assertions that define the scope of two trifecta legs','2026-03-01 23:56:36'),(29,'The patterns described in this source were developed and validated across multiple client engagements at QuantumBlack, AI by McKinsey, and are stated to be running in production deployments.',5,'case_study',NULL,'{\"notes\": \"Credible practitioner claim from named firm. Production deployment is stated but not independently verified.\", \"credibility\": 2, \"evaluated_at\": \"2026-03-02 00:40:21.000000\", \"independence\": \"original\", \"verifiability\": \"verifiable\"}',NULL,'Production validation claim â€” no external audit; practitioner account','2026-03-02 00:35:28'),(30,'ARK (Agents at Scale Runtime for Kubernetes) is released as open source at github.com/mckinsey/agents-at-scale-ark. It is described as provider-agnostic and codifies patterns from dozens of agentic application projects, including built-in Kubernetes CRDs for agents, models, memory, tools, and evaluation.',5,'case_study','github.com/mckinsey/agents-at-scale-ark','{\"notes\": \"GitHub URL is publicly verifiable. ARK repo existence can be confirmed directly.\", \"credibility\": 2, \"evaluated_at\": \"2026-03-02 00:40:21.000000\", \"independence\": \"original\", \"verifiability\": \"verified\"}',NULL,NULL,'2026-03-02 00:35:28'),(31,'The two-layer architecture — deterministic orchestration plus bounded agent execution — is described as the consistent pattern across all successful implementations in the QuantumBlack client portfolio.',5,'expert_opinion',NULL,'{\"notes\": \"Expert opinion from practitioner at established firm. Consistent with patterns described across the source. No independent verification available.\", \"credibility\": 2, \"evaluated_at\": \"2026-03-02 00:40:21.000000\", \"independence\": \"original\", \"verifiability\": \"verifiable\"}',NULL,'Asserted without enumerated case count or failure rate','2026-03-02 00:35:28'),(32,'Self-orchestrating agents on larger codebases exhibited specific failure modes: skipped steps, circular dependencies, and analysis loops. These are reported as observed behaviors, not hypothetical risks.',5,'anecdotal',NULL,'{\"notes\": \"Anecdotal observation from client engagements. Specific failure modes are plausible but no benchmarks or controlled comparisons provided. Single practitioner perspective.\", \"credibility\": 3, \"evaluated_at\": \"2026-03-02 00:40:21.000000\", \"independence\": \"original\", \"verifiability\": \"verifiable\"}',NULL,'No quantitative data; practitioner observation from client work','2026-03-02 00:35:28'),(33,'Spec Kit and Kiro share the same key design decision: separating persistent project context from per-feature specifications, both stored in the repository. The source asserts this without citation or detail about how the tools were compared.',5,'expert_opinion',NULL,'{\"notes\": \"Asserted without citation or detail about how the tools were evaluated. The claim may be accurate but is unsubstantiated in the source. Would require independent confirmation against Spec Kit and Kiro documentation.\", \"credibility\": 3, \"evaluated_at\": \"2026-03-02 00:40:21.000000\", \"independence\": \"original\", \"verifiability\": \"verifiable\"}',NULL,'Unverified comparative assertion; source acknowledges no citation provided','2026-03-02 00:35:28'),(34,'The knowledge agent workflow example: during feature creation, a requirements agent calls the knowledge agent multiple times. One documented query: \"Should notifications be sent synchronously or via a queue?\" Logged assumption: \"Using async queue-based delivery (not synchronous).\" These assumptions surface as discrete, structured items in the pull request diff — reviewable and correctable.',5,'case_study','Should notifications be sent synchronously or via a queue?','{\"notes\": \"Concrete example with verbatim quote. Specific enough to be representative of the actual pattern. Illustrative rather than exhaustive.\", \"credibility\": 2, \"evaluated_at\": \"2026-03-02 00:40:21.000000\", \"independence\": \"original\", \"verifiability\": \"verifiable\"}',NULL,'Concrete implementation example with specific query and logged assumption','2026-03-02 00:35:28'),(35,'When a reviewer approves a PR, they approve the logged assumptions alongside the code. When they reject an assumption, the agent reworks with corrected information, and the correction becomes a documented decision that future agents can retrieve.',5,'expert_opinion',NULL,'{\"notes\": \"Describes a coherent and plausible workflow. Verifiable in principle against ARK implementation but not independently confirmed here.\", \"credibility\": 2, \"evaluated_at\": \"2026-03-02 00:40:21.000000\", \"independence\": \"original\", \"verifiability\": \"verifiable\"}',NULL,NULL,'2026-03-02 00:35:28'),(36,'The workflow engine enforces rules including: requirements must be complete before task generation begins; architecture must be reviewed before implementation starts; tasks can only execute when their dependencies are satisfied.',5,'case_study',NULL,'{\"notes\": \"Specific, concrete rules stated by the source. Consistent with the deterministic orchestration architecture described throughout.\", \"credibility\": 2, \"evaluated_at\": \"2026-03-02 00:40:21.000000\", \"independence\": \"original\", \"verifiability\": \"verifiable\"}',NULL,NULL,'2026-03-02 00:35:28'),(37,'Evaluation runs in two sequential layers at end of each phase: (1) deterministic checks — linters, test suites, structural validation including frontmatter presence, required section structure, cross-reference resolution; (2) critic agent for checks requiring judgment. If either layer rejects output, the producing agent iterates until both pass.',5,'case_study',NULL,'{\"notes\": \"Detailed description of evaluation architecture. Specific enough to be actionable. Verifiable in principle against ARK codebase.\", \"credibility\": 2, \"evaluated_at\": \"2026-03-02 00:40:21.000000\", \"independence\": \"original\", \"verifiability\": \"verifiable\"}',NULL,NULL,'2026-03-02 00:35:28'),(38,'Folder and naming conventions (e.g., specs/REQ-001-*/, context/, REQ-* prefixes) serve dual purpose: organizing artifacts for human developers and enabling the workflow engine to parse parent-child relationships and compute task order programmatically.',5,'case_study',NULL,'{\"notes\": \"Specific folder paths and naming patterns provided. Verifiable against ARK repository conventions.\", \"credibility\": 2, \"evaluated_at\": \"2026-03-02 00:40:21.000000\", \"independence\": \"original\", \"verifiability\": \"verifiable\"}',NULL,NULL,'2026-03-02 00:35:28'),(39,'The source explicitly states: no quantitative benchmarks are provided. Performance claims — that deterministic orchestration outperforms self-orchestrating agents, that specialized agents outperform general ones — are presented as patterns observed across client engagements but are not backed by controlled measurements or published data.',5,'expert_opinion',NULL,'{\"notes\": \"Source explicitly acknowledges lack of quantitative benchmarks. This is a factually certain statement about what the source does and does not contain â€” highest credibility as a limitation disclosure.\", \"credibility\": 1, \"evaluated_at\": \"2026-03-02 00:40:21.000000\", \"independence\": \"original\", \"verifiability\": \"verified\"}',NULL,'Source self-reports this limitation explicitly in Gaps and Caveats section','2026-03-02 00:35:28'),(40,'The source is authored by a QuantumBlack practitioner and prominently references QuantumBlack tooling (ARK). The open-source release of ARK is mentioned in both the introduction and the conclusion, which the source acknowledges introduces potential promotional framing.',5,'expert_opinion',NULL,'{\"notes\": \"Source self-reports its own potential promotional framing. Observable and verifiable directly from the source text. Highest credibility as a documented self-disclosure.\", \"credibility\": 1, \"evaluated_at\": \"2026-03-02 00:40:21.000000\", \"independence\": \"original\", \"verifiability\": \"verified\"}',NULL,'Source acknowledges potential bias; important credibility qualifier','2026-03-02 00:35:28'),(41,'The post focuses on greenfield feature development and does not address how the patterns apply to legacy codebase migration, incident response, or other development scenarios that do not follow a clean requirements-to-implementation flow.',5,'expert_opinion',NULL,'{\"notes\": \"Factually accurate gap statement â€” the source does not address legacy migration or incident response. Verifiable by inspection of source content.\", \"credibility\": 1, \"evaluated_at\": \"2026-03-02 00:40:21.000000\", \"independence\": \"original\", \"verifiability\": \"verified\"}',NULL,'Scope limitation explicitly acknowledged by source','2026-03-02 00:35:28'),(42,'Artifact status is tracked in frontmatter (draft, in-review, approved, complete). Folder conventions and naming prefixes allow the workflow engine to parse parent-child relationships and compute task order programmatically, making the system machine-readable without a separate configuration layer.',5,'case_study',NULL,'{\"notes\": \"Specific technical detail about artifact status tracking in frontmatter. Consistent with conventions described elsewhere in the source. Verifiable against ARK implementation.\", \"credibility\": 2, \"evaluated_at\": \"2026-03-02 00:40:21.000000\", \"independence\": \"original\", \"verifiability\": \"verifiable\"}',NULL,NULL,'2026-03-02 00:35:28'),(43,'The specialized agent model is explicitly compared by the source to a microservices architecture — trading one complex system for multiple simpler systems plus the orchestration cost of managing interfaces. This framing positions agent complexity as an architectural problem with established software engineering solutions.',5,'expert_opinion','trading one complex system for multiple simpler systems plus the orchestration cost of managing interfaces between them','{\"notes\": \"Verbatim quote from source. The analogy is clearly attributed to the author. Credible as a representation of the author\'s framing.\", \"credibility\": 2, \"evaluated_at\": \"2026-03-02 00:40:21.000000\", \"independence\": \"original\", \"verifiability\": \"verified\"}',NULL,NULL,'2026-03-02 00:35:28'),(44,'The source directly counters the popular narrative that more capable models with more autonomy are inherently better, asserting instead that constraints and structure are what enable reliable output — not raw capability.',5,'expert_opinion','value from AI agents comes when they operate inside conventions, structured specifications, and deterministic processes','{\"notes\": \"Verbatim quote from source. Accurately captures the author\'s explicit counter-positioning against autonomy-maximalist narratives.\", \"credibility\": 2, \"evaluated_at\": \"2026-03-02 00:40:21.000000\", \"independence\": \"original\", \"verifiability\": \"verified\"}',NULL,NULL,'2026-03-02 00:35:28');
